The author&#39;s solution uses the format mini-language&#39;s definition of &quot;precision&quot; for strings. With floating-point values, it is the expected number of digits.

    &gt;&gt;&gt; &quot;{:.1}&quot;.format(3.14159)
    &#39;3e+00&#39;
    &gt;&gt;&gt; &quot;{:.2}&quot;.format(3.14159)
    &#39;3.1&#39;

For strings, it&#39;s the maximum field width.

    &gt;&gt;&gt; &quot;{:.1}&quot;.format(&quot;foo&quot;)
    &#39;f&#39;
    &gt;&gt;&gt; &quot;{:.2}&quot;.format(&quot;foo&quot;)
    &#39;fo&#39;

From the [documentation](https://docs.python.org/3.7/library/string.html#format-specification-mini-language):

&gt;The precision is a decimal number indicating how many digits should be displayed after the decimal point for a floating point value formatted with &#39;f&#39; and &#39;F&#39;, or before and after the decimal point for a floating point value formatted with &#39;g&#39; or &#39;G&#39;. **For non-number types the field indicates the maximum field size - in other words, how many characters will be used from the field content.** The precision is not allowed for integer values.

